{{Japanese related|resources| * [http://tisc.isc.u-toyama.ac.jp/self/quiz_particles.html Particles quiz] at the Toyama International Student Center Self Japanese Learning Support Site. * [[w:Japanese particles]]}} {{Japanese related|content| * [[../Sentence ending particles/]]}} The Japanese language uses post-position particles (; ) to denote the direction of an action and who is performing the action. They consistently come after the word that they modify.
There are three particles used very frequently in the language: , and . This module covers these along with a few other common ones but an exhaustive list would run very long.
== The topic and subject markers and ==
The particle "" (pronounced as "" when used as a particle) is the ''topic marker'' denoting topic of discussion, while "" is the ''subject marker'' and marks a noun that performs an action. The difference between the two tends to cause confusion among beginners but their usage can be summed up as matter of focus.
The topic particle "" is used when introducing a topic and gives focus to the ''action'' of the sentence (i.e., the verb or the adjective). The subject marker "" is used when emphasising the subject giving focus to the ''subject'' of the action.
One can also think of it as replacing "~" with the phrase "as for ~", "on the topic of ~" or "regarding ~" to distinguish it from "". While these phrases aren't common in English we can use these expressions here to better show the main difference between "" and "". {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || The cat is eating (or: Regarding the cat, it is eating.) |- | '''''' || The ''cat'' is eating (as opposed to someone else). |- | '''''' || You are strong. |- | '''''' || ''You'' are strong (only you and not anyone else) |- | '''''' || That's the telephone. |- | '''''' || ''That's'' the telephone (and not anything else) |}
The difference can also be displayed by using both subject and topic markers in one sentence: {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' '''''' || I like you. (Or literally: as for me, like you.) |- | '''''' '''''' || I dislike/hate wasabi. (Or: As for me, hate wasabi.) |- | '''''' '''''' || Your English is good! (Or: As for you, English good!) |} One has to be careful using both "" and "" in one sentence. If a verb is actually acting on the (direct) subject, usually a different particle (like ) has to be used.
"" is generally more flexible, because the "it" can be assumed, and is therefore recommended to novices who have not grasped the difference between the two.
"" also has the specialized function of being used for comparisons as well. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || There is a cat. |- | '''''' || There is a dog. |- | '''''' , '''''' || The cat is eating, but the dog is not. |}
Often the grammatical subject may also be the topic. In this case, "" normally replaces "". However, if the subject is never known, you cannot use "" and must use "". This is similar to using pronouns: You can't state, "It is over there", without first stating what "it" may be.
== The direct object marker ==
The particle "" (pronounced "") is the ''direct object marker'' and marks the recipient of an action. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || To drink sake. |- | '''''' || To read a magazine. |- | '''''' || The cat is drinking water. |}
It also indicates the place through which the action occurs: {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || To fly through the sky |- | '''''' || To walk down the street |}
As with much of the language, parts of a sentence that can be assumed from context are often omitted and the direct object particle is commonly dropped in conversational (colloquial) Japanese.
== The indirect object marker ==
"" marks the verb's ''indirect object'' (i.e. the destination of a targeted verb action) translating as "to", "in", "at" or "by". It also indicates the location touched or affected by an event or action: {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Fly '''to''' the stars. |- | '''''' || Give a present '''to''' a friend. |- | '''''' || To tell (something) to the teacher. |- | '''''' || To be '''in''' school. |- | '''''' || To be '''at''' home. |- | '''''' || To meet '''on''' Saturday |}
The particle "" described below is used exclusively for marking the destination.
== The destination marker == (pronounced "" when used as a particle) indicates the direction of an action, roughly the equivalent of "to" or "toward" in English. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Mother is going to the store. |- | '''''' || To go to Tokyo. |}
== The question marker ==
Placing at the end of a sentence changes a statement into a question. Use it at the end of a verb to make it a question, or at the end of an interrogative [[../Pro-forms|pro-form]] to make it into a demonstrative pronoun.
{| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Am I a man? |- | '''''' || How do you describe this? |- | '''''' || Is there a cat? |- | '''''' ''''''|| Did you go somewhere? |}
For more on the question marker, see: [[../Sentence ending particles/]].
== The possessive marker ==
"", is most commonly used as a ''possessive marker'' (similar to the English "'s"). {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || The teacher''''s''' apple |- | '''''' || '''My''' bag. |- | '''''' || '''His''' watch. |} The particle can also function as a noun link, indicating that the preceding noun (or [[Japanese/Lessons/Na-adjectives|adjectival noun]]) modifies the following noun. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Buildings '''in/of''' Tokyo. |- | '''''' || A green book. |} It can also be used for ''nominalisation'', converting verbs and [[Japanese/Lessons/I-adjectives|(proper) adjectives]] into nouns. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Read'''ing''' is good. |} Note that in this last example two particles are used together: and : the first makes the action a noun, and the second tells that this action is what the sentence is all about.
== The exhaustive list conjunction ==
This particle acts as a conjunction on the words it separates. Unlike conjunctions of more than two words in English, where only the last two are separated with an "and" and the rest with commas, the Japanese conjunction separates each word and commas are not used. {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || This '''and''' that are green. |- | '''''' || A book '''and''' a magazine. |- | '''''' '''''' '''''' || There is a pen''',''' a pencil''',''' an eraser '''and''' a ruler in the bag. |}
This applies to exhaustive lists, i.e. when all objects are explicitly mentioned.
The particle is used to indicate parallelism with the subject, often meaning "with": {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || I spoke '''with''' him. |- | '''''' || {I/He/She/They} went '''with''' her. |- | '''''' || (I) played tennis with Smith" |- | '''''' || I will marry you. (I will get married '''with''' you) |}
== The incomplete list marker ==
This particle is used to connect various words implying that the listing is not exhaustive. The particle "" may be added after the list to emphasise that the list is incomplete. {| class="wikitable" | Noun || Particle || Noun || ... | style="color:gray" | |} {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || There are books '''and''' pens (among other things). |- | '''''' || A book '''and''' a magazine (among other things). |- | '''''' '''''' '''''' || (I) need eggs''',''' salad''',''' chicken '''and such'''. |}
== The "also" marker ==
is quite simply a marker that says "also". It replaces the particles , and but can also follow other particles. This can also be used to form a large list of words all acting as though one of the basic particles (, , or ) were affecting the whole list. {| class="wikitable" | Subject || Particle || Verb |} {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || The cat also drinks. |- | '''''' || I'm going too. |- | '''''' '''''' '''''' '''''' || Boys, girls, women and men are human. |}
{{Japanese related|content| * [[../Pro-forms/]]}} Worth noting is that used with an interrogative pro-form (e.g. who, where, how) the particle negates the pro-form: {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | || anybody |- | e.g. || General knowledge. |- | || nobody |- | e.g. || Nobody's here. |}
== The means particle ==
The particle can be used in several situations indicating means. These can be for example an instrument, a location or a language.
{| class="wikitable" | Means || Particle || Verb |} {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || '''By''' what means do you go to University? |- | '''''' || I go '''by''' bicycle. |- | '''''' || I go '''by''' car. |- | '''''' || I eat '''at''' a restaurant. |- | '''''' || I played tennis with Smith '''at''' the park." |- | '''''' || To learn '''at''' school. |}
As a note of interest, the from the copula is also actually an instrumental-maker. marks the whole previous expression instrumental to the verb . However, this is the classical meaning of the copula and rarely ''explicitly'' treated this way in modern Japanese.
== Origin and limit and ==
These particles indicate the starting point or border of an action. This may be a location as well as a time and corresponds roughly with "from" and "until". {| {{Japanese example}} | style="width:20em" | '''''' || Come '''from''' Tokyo. |- | '''''' || To go '''to''' the mountains. |- | {{furi||}}{{furi|9|}}'''''' {{furi|5|}}'''''' | The hours are '''from''' 9 '''to''' 5. |}
